title: For Sale:  Seaco Hardness Tester
postcontent:
Taken From Reddings Site
A SAECO Lead Hardness Tester will pay for itself many times over by allowing you to convert inexpensive scrap lead of unknown composition into casting alloy of known and reproduceable hardness. It provides a standard by which you can check the quality of purchased cast bullets.

The SAECO Lead Hardness Tester measures alloy  hardness by determining the depth of penetration of a  hardened steel indenter into a bullet. Relative hardness of  the bullet is read off a vernier scale.

	Relative Hardness
	SAECO 	Brinell
(Approx.)
Pure lead . . . . . . . . . . . 	0-1 	5
1:20 tin: lead . . . . . . . . 	6-7 	10
5:5:90 tin:
antimony: lead . . . . . 	7-8 	15
2:6:92 (taracorp) . . . . . 	8-9 	16-17
(magnum alloy)
5:10:85 (linotype) . . . . 	9-10 	22

The vernier scale is calibrated in arbitrary units from 0 for pure lead up to a SAECO hardness of 10. We have found  that a SAECO hardness of at least 6 is required for medium velocities in handguns and a SAECO hardness of over 8 for Magnum handgun and gas check rifle bullets. As a point of reference, wheelweights vary in composition and hardness but usually test between 7 and 9, while linotype registers approx. 10.

42000   SEACO Lead Hardness Tester    $239.00 --Compare to 130.00

The new Beretta Px4 Storm pistol is the most advanced expression of technological and aesthetic features in a semiautomatic sidearm. Built around a modular concept that a pistol can be adapted to different needs and modes of operations, without compromising on ergonomics and the renowned Beretta reliability and performance, the Px4 Storm emphasizes power, ease of handling, performance and reliability.

Manufactured in three calibers, the Px4 Storm uses an exclusive Beretta designed innovative locked-breech with a rotating barrel system, the strongest action to date.

The light yet durable frame employs modern thermoplastic technology through the use of technopolymer reinforced fiberglass. Modular structure, ergonomics and interchangeability of parts make the Px4 Storm the ideal firearm for law-enforcement use, as well as personal defense.

1. Accessory Rail: The frame of the Px4 Storm has an integral Picatinny MILSTD-1913 rail for rapid attachment of tactical lights and laser aiming devices.
2. Slide: The sides of the slide are smooth and offer snag-proof insertion and removal of the pistol from its holster. The front and rear serrations on the slide facilitate slide operation and safety control in both wet or dry conditions.
3. Visible Automatic Firing Pin Block: The front part of the firing pin is blocked from any forward movement until the trigger is pulled completely back. The block is located rearward, far away from the fouling and debris of the breech face. Since the block is visible, the user may ascertain its proper operation at any time. Even if the pistol falls and strikes the ground muzzle down, the firing pin will not strike the primer.
4. 3-Dot Sight System: Features a white ‘3-dot’ sight pattern for quick acquisition of the target. The rear sight is designed to provide a front projection so that, in an emergency, the user may retract the slide single-handedly by pushing the rear sight against the edge of a table, door, etc.

The safety lever also functions as the pistol’s decocking lever. When pushed down, the rear part of the firing pin (striker) is rotated out of alignment with the front part of the firing pin. (NOTE: Type C does not have an external safety/decocking lever). Additional hammer drop catch (half cock notch) prevents striking of the firing pin unit in the remote chance of unintentional hammer drop.
6. External Hammer Design: A traditional feature of Beretta pistols, this design provides the most energy to the firing pin, virtually eliminating the possibility of misfires due to light primer strikes. Also provides an immediate visual and tactile indicator as to the cocked/uncocked status of the pistol.
7. Individual Size Grips: Pistol may be configured with small, medium or large backstraps to individually fit the hand of each shooter. The backstraps are checkered to ensure a firm grip in both wet or dry shooting conditions. Three backstraps included with every pistol.

title: For Sale:  NIB Barrett M107A1 w/ BORS
postcontent:
Barret M107A1

It may be related to the Model 82A1®/M107®, but the M107A1 is far from a simple evolution. Driven by the demands of combat, every component was re-engineered to be lighter yet stronger. The result? A high-performance rifle that weighs five pounds less than the original M107, but is every bit as tough.

Designed to be used with a suppressor, this one-of-a-kind rifle allows you to combine signature reduction capabilities with the flawless reliability of the original Barrett M107, but with a rifle weight reduction of 5 pounds. An all new bolt carrier group has been designed and is key to making the rifle suppressor-ready. Its steel four-port cylindrical muzzle brake is engineered to work seamlessly with a quick-attach Barrett QDL Suppressor.

The lightweight aluminum upper receiver features an integrated 27 MOA optics rail. Inside the upper receiver, the bolt carrier rides on a hardened steel anti-wear strip for added durability. A thermal-guard cheek piece protects the user's face from extreme heat or cold.

Advanced design and manufacturing make the M107A1 more precise than ever. The rear barrel stop and front barrel bushing are bolted and bonded with a high strength compound. A titanium barrel key and fully-chrome-lined bore and chamber add to the rifle's durability.

Enhanced modularity is also a key feature of the M107A1. The rail-mounted aluminum rear grip can easily be reconfigured. The newly designed titanium and polymer monopod is adjustable from either side.

The M107A1 rifle's lower receiver includes a new aluminum recoil buffer system that's optimized for use with the Barrett QDL Suppressor. The bolt carrier's components are protected with a mix of ultra-hard coatings and advanced nickel Teflon® plating that increases lubricity, is corrosion-resistant and greatly eases cleaning.

Numbered witness holes on the magazine are just another example of how even the smallest detail makes a powerful difference.

B.O.R.S. Sight (For Leupold Mark IV)

The Barrett Optical Ranging System (BORS) is an integrated ballistics computer that mounts directly on the riflescope and couples to the elevation knob.

BORS instantly takes care of the data work by drawing from several tables and taking into account a number of real-time external factors so you can focus on the task of achieving first round hits.

After determining the range to target, simply turn the elevation knob until the BORS screen matches your target's distance. Internal sensors automatically calculate the ballistic solution. BORS compensates for temperature and barometric pressure, calculates angle cosine and displays rifle cant.

The BORS kit includes the proprietary Barrett Ballistic PC Software that's pre-programmed with a library selected by Barrett. BORS USB data cable allows the transfer of user programmable custom loads to BORS from his or her computer.

Designed primarily to withstand military operations, BORS is rugged and able to operate with a variety of scopes, calibers and rifles.

*Barrett Ballistic Software requires Windows XP or higher, and is not directly MAC OS compatible.

*Buyer pays shipping if not available for local pick up.

DON'T SEND MONEY ORDERS OFF EXPECTING SOMETHING TO BE DELIVERED TO YOU , 9 TIMES OUT OF 10 IT WON'T BE! There are honest sellers out there, that will conduct an honest transaction but is it worth the risk? Just remember Armslist is great for face to face deals, if you want to order out of state, stick to Gunbroker where you can at least see feedback ratings.

You there. Yeah, you. You, sitting on the couch with your stretchy shorts on with the laptop on your lap reading this ad. Yeah, the lead photo was bad ass huh? You just *had* to stop on this ad... but... unfortunately, this ad may not be for you. You may want to hit the back button now and stop reading, because this ad, and this weapon, well, they'll change your life and you just may not be ready for what's in store for you... or are you? 

Well, you're still reading this so you haven't hit the back button. Good, you passed the second test. The first test required that you know a freakin' straight-up operator's weapon when you see one and, well, you clicked on this ad so there's a spark of operator in ya.  The second test required that your default has to be to NOT follow the damn rules. I told you not to keep reading; you told me to fuck off and kept reading so, you're good... so far. 

Now, listen, you've read this far so that means that together we've already weeded out the gun collector types because this weapon is dirty, it's scratched up and I'm pretty sure there's a little dried blood on the grips. This gun is a collector's nightmare. Congratulations, you're officially more operator than those guys, but, don't get ahead of yourself because you still may be a douche and, frankly, it doesn't take much to be more operator than the gun collector guys. 

Ok, so now we need to determine in you're a mall ninja. Mall ninjas need not apply for the RIGHT to own this weapon, because a weapon like this needs a constant diet of real life ops or at least some dirty ass training for real life ops and, I can assure you that running around your mom's house in your airsoft gear clearing rooms while she's at work IS NOT operator and this weapon will straight up lose-its-shit if it's placed into that type of environment. One doesn't simple *BUY* a weapon with this much character; one *adopts* a weapon like this and you keep it in your care, custody and control until you can find the next qualified owner to hand it off to. So, if you're not willing to keep it for life or be responsible for finding its next qualified home then, please, hit that back button we were talking about earlier because this is simply not your weapon. 

Ok, so, I'm going to assume that you're not a mall ninja because a mall ninja would have pissed his pants at the, very real, possibility of me sniffing his ass out upon our eventual face-to-face meeting. Good, you're still legit and you're getting closer to being qualified so keep reading. 

Now, let me tell you about this weapon. You need to know who she is and what she likes before you can commit. Number one, this is a dirty little bitch. She doesn't like to be fully cleaned after use. Shoot her, come home, run a bore snake through her barrel, a couple of drops of some lube and hit her lower with an air compressor and stick her ass back in the holster. Oh yeah, I should have mentioned, this gun insists on living in a holster. Weapons like this can't survive in some padded ass zipper case or on a felt-padded shelf in a climate-controlled safe. She needs to be in a holster and if that holster isn't on your damn hip then it needs to be in your damn truck , and yes I said "truck" (but an SUV is acceptable too, just not a damned Volvo).

Ok, so now that you she likes to be dirty and that she insists on accompanying you everywhere you go, like a good dog (not a Cocker Spaniel either, but a real dog with no papers), you need to know what NOT to do with her. 

Here's the list of things she hates:
1) She won't wear anything from "Condor" or "Uncle Mike's". If you can't afford to put her in a real holster from London Bridge Trading or Safariland or some other reputable manufacture then please, dude, the back button, now. 
2) She WILL NOT SET FOOT in an indoor range. Please, for the love of all things holy, do not take this weapon to some stupid gun store range where you have to stand stationary in a damed phone booth and shoot one round no faster than every 7 seconds at a stupid ass stationary paper bull's eye target. Just really, stop right here if that's your thing because this beauty has seen too much real-world action and too much hardcore training to go back to the training wheels. This weapon needs to be kicking in doors or rolling around in the damn mud at an outdoor range... preferably not even a "real" range but some dude's property out in the sticks. 
3) She won't pose for photos for you to post on some Internet message board forum that is over run by 13yo boys trying to pose as spec ops guys. She bitched and moaned about posing for the three photos you're seeing on this ad and I promised her that it was for a good cause. She's still pissed though. She's not a show off, she's worker. 
4) I promised her you wouldn't put stupid shit on her. That means no lazers, optics, those rubber slip-on grip things, aftermarket magazines or funnel wells or any of the stupid shit you see in gun magazines. 
5) Don't email me asking date codes or round counts. If you have to ask, well, you're not operator enough for a weapon like her. She shoots straight and works. Period. 

Essentially, the rules above boil down to one thing: Don't be that guy. Don't be the guy that takes a weapon with a proud heritage and work history and turns her into a cheap slut or a showpiece. This weapon has had a few owners over her years, and with them she's literally seen conflicts in far off lands in the hands of a security contractor, has stacked-up to be first through the door in real SWAT operations with another owner, proudly protected the family of a responsible citizen and has served homeland security duties with another. She's forgotten more ops than most guns will ever know. She's legit, she has the scars to prove it and she still has a lot to give. 

So, anyway, incase you couldn't tell form the photos, she's an HK USP .45 and she comes with three 12rd German made original HK mags, her original case (which she hates so don't ask her to go in it) and her owner's manual... I'll sum up the owner's manual: Pull trigger = go bang. Her grip has been subtly stippled... trust me, you'll like it.
